The new anti-globalization backlash
PRINCETON – A palpable sense of unease was felt during the last G-7 summit in Ise-Shima, Japan.
At the next meeting of the world's leading developed economies' leaders, no one can predict which of them will be the populists in revolt.
President Donald Trump could represent the United States, or President Marine Le Pen could represent France.
They could sit with British Prime Minister Boris Johnson, Italian Prime Minister Beppe Grillo, or even German Chancellor Frauke Petry.
Chacun d'eux pourrait se faire le champion du nationalisme et de l'isolationnisme, sous une forme ou une autre.
The anti-globalization backlash has been going on for two decades.
At the end of the 20th century, the global trend seemed to be towards convergence, and people seemed to be consuming the same products everywhere.
McDonald's illustrated this kind of globalization: breaking the stores of this chain had become a standard form of protest against globalization.
But lately, the nature of globalization has changed, as has the reaction against it.
Although the world is still becoming more interconnected, there is a feeling that we understand foreigners less.
In response to the evolution of consumer preferences (which are increasingly sophisticated), companies are relocating their production closer to the markets where goods will be sold.
This weakens the growth of international trade.
This kind of "on-shore" anchoring is not new.
In the 1970s and 1980s, Americans feared that the United States would be flooded by Japanese automobiles. They then began producing these automobiles domestically.
Currently, most Japanese cars sold in the United States are manufactured in the United States. But the reversal of merchandise globalization is now easier than ever, thanks to advancements in robotics engineering and the development of processes like 3D printing.
Thus, today's criticism of globalization tends to focus less on commercial issues.
However, this evolution does not reflect only the slowdown in trade growth.
Rich country consumers are much more comfortable with foreign products; in some cases, they are even dependent on them, from constantly updated electronics to cheap, fast-fashion items that have become dominant in advanced economies.
Instead of rejecting foreign goods, current critics of globalization reject foreigners.
The disputes over investor protection clauses in trade agreements like the Trans-Pacific Partnership or the Transatlantic Trade and Investment Partnership center on concerns about obscure tribunals protecting foreign company interests and allegedly undermining national sovereignty.
Then there is the global refugee crisis: in Europe, in particular, anxiety over this influx might be a harbinger of broader rejection of immigration from failed and impoverished states.
Why are populations in advanced countries so afraid of foreigners?
It's not as if they've never been exposed to other cultures.
Many citizens of these countries travel constantly to distant destinations and hundreds of millions of people worldwide head to advanced economies each year.
The problem lies in the way we travel.
Today, we tend to experience things quickly and superficially rather than immersing ourselves in a culture.
But as modern game theory teaches us, a single interaction is very different from ongoing contact.
If participants know they have a unique and limited experience, they have no interest in building a deeper base of understanding or cooperation.
An ongoing exchange is necessary to foster trust.
The result of the superficial approach to current travels is evident for any major tourist destination.
Restaurants are unlikely to provide good or simply honest service to people who are surely not going to return.
Restaurants serve mediocre (or worse) food without a smile, taxi drivers cheat, hoteliers lie about their facilities.
Moreover, this little game can be interrupted.
Where tourism has become a source of foreign revenue, it also becomes an attractive target for terrorists who base their ideology on anti-Western resentment.
A few attacks in places like Bali or the Red Sea resorts would be enough to cause a deep economic destabilization.
Tourism businesses respond to such risks by minimizing contact with the local population.
The emblem of modern tourism is a giant cruise ship, where passengers can spend a few hours at each stop (to visit a beautiful Caribbean island or an ancient Mediterranean port), but always sleep in the same bed.
The new Harmony of the Seas cruise ship from Royal Caribbean aims to recreate all climates of the world.
Indeed, this ship, which is over 30 meters long and could contain a tropical park and an ice rink (as well as its 23 pools and 42 bars), contains the Eiffel Tower.
Bus and train tour companies ensure the safety of their clients by limiting their time at famous sites just enough to take a few pictures.
This style of travel constrains the capacity of local infrastructure.
There is often not enough space to walk along the canals of Venice or along the path leading to the Acropolis.
This approach reinforces mutual misunderstanding.
Visitors stay within the limits of their pre-planned excursions, encountering only scammers who offer trinkets or extremely expensive taxi rides.
The locals do not appreciate the groups of tourists who gather around their most beautiful sites.
No one feels particularly involved, nor do they maintain any sense of trust.
It is easy to feel nostalgic for the time when tourism went hand in hand with longer stays and ongoing encounters with very different cultures.
It would obviously be impossible for the current number of visitors to stay weeks or months in old monasteries.
But it is possible to imagine certain configurations in which visitors and their hosts could interact in a more personal manner.
Airbnb, for example, can provide a much more appealing experience than a hotel or, worse, a cruise ship.
Is there an equivalent policy to Airbnb?
Could world leaders attend summits like the G-7 by living and working for an extended period in a foreign country?
Shortly after the United States entered World War II, Winston Churchill famously moved into the White House for 24 days to consolidate the transatlantic alliance between Britain and the United States, deepening his relationship with Franklin Roosevelt.
This level of familiarity could well be the greatest enemy of today's anti-globalist populists.
